                <h2>The aging positivity effect</h2>
                <p>
                    The aging positivity effect refers to the tendency for older adults to focus on positive over negative emotional stimuli.
                    Given the potentially harmful consequences of avoiding negative information, we hypothesized that this aging positivity effect may provide benefits that offset its costs.
                    There is a well-established link between positivity and health, and keeping healthy is a major concern for older adults, suggesting that the positivity effect could
                    be maintained because it confers health benefits. We found that older adults who recalled more positive information at initial testing showed blood markers
                    indicative of better immune functioning (increased CD4 counts and decreased CD4 activation) one and two years later, suggesting that older adults may show a positivity
                    effect in part to combat increasing health challenges.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
