                <h2>The consequences of expressing and suppressing positive emotions</h2>
                <p>
                    Typically, there are personal and social benefits to expressing positive emotion, and personal and social costs to suppressing positive emotion.
                    We examine the contextual boundaries of these effects, investigating situations in which down-regulating positive emotions may have social benefits.
                    In three studies, we found that winners who express positive emotions are perceived negatively, an effect that is mediated through the perception that expressive
                    winners are hubristically prideful (Kalokerinos, Greenaway, Pedder, & Margetts, in press). We’re currently investigating the effects of emotion expression and suppression
                    on personality perception, the costs and benefits of reappraisal and suppression as positive emotion down-regulation strategies, and the role of testosterone in emotion
                    expression and regulation.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
