            <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h2>Stereotype threat in organizations</h2>
                <p>
                    Negative stereotypes about different groups persist in organizations. Employees from such groups may experience stereotype threat, or the concern that they are being judged
                    on the basis of demeaning stereotypes about groups to which they belong. Our empirical work in this area has thus far focused on older workers, an important and understudied
                    work group. We found that stereotype threat among older workers is associated with negative work attitudes and greater intentions to retire (von Hippel, Kalokerinos, & Henry, 2013).
                    We’ve followed up this empirical work with a focal article in Industrial and Organizational Psychology: Perspectives on Science and Practice (Kalokerinos, von Hippel, & Zacher, in press),
                    in which we argue that stereotype threat is important for a variety of organizational outcomes. We’re currently investigating why stereotype threat seems to have problematic
                    consequences for older, but not younger, workers, and whether stereotype threat may influence working women’s interest in, and use of, work-family policies.
                </p>
            </div>
